  "prompt": "Is Hinduism monotheistic or polytheistic?",
  "response": "Hinduism is complex and can be viewed from different perspectives:\n\n1. Polytheistic aspects:\n- Multiple gods and goddesses are worshipped\n- Numerous deities like Shiva, Vishnu, Krishna, Durga, etc.\n\n2. Monotheistic/Pantheistic aspects:\n- Many Hindus believe in Brahman, a supreme universal spirit/cosmic principle\n- Different deities are often seen as manifestations or aspects of this single divine essence\n- Some traditions view gods as different expressions of one ultimate reality\n\n3. Philosophical perspectives:\n- Some schools of Hinduism are henotheistic (focusing on one god while acknowledging others)\n- Advaita Vedanta philosophy sees ultimate reality as non-dual (one interconnected divine essence)\n\nSo Hinduism doesn't fit neatly into monotheistic or polytheistic categories. It's more accurate to describe it as a complex religious tradition with multiple theological interpretations that can incorporate elements of both monotheism and polytheism.\n\nThe specific perspective depends on the particular Hindu tradition, philosophical school, and individual interpretation.",
